{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17526094","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17526094"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:20:20+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:20:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14117"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14117","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14117"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.33,0.46,0.12,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6797"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58471"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6797","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6797"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14117"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43887"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"2969"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"3696"},{"type":"tags","id":"9256"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15191"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18244"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18245"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58471","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/58471"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of chronic diarrhoea, weight loss, and fatigue. She recently returned from a six-month backpacking trip through Southeast Asia. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears unwell with a pulse rate of 90/min, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. Her abdomen is soft and non-tender. Blood tests show an anaemia with low folate and vitamin B12 levels.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following investigations is most likely to confirm the diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hydrogen breath test","Small bowel biopsy","Stool culture","Colonoscopy","Abdominal CT scan"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s presentation is highly suggestive of tropical sprue, a malabsorption syndrome typically acquired during extended stays in tropical regions. The chronic diarrhoea, weight loss, and nutritional deficiencies (anaemia, low folate and B12) are characteristic features. While several investigations can be helpful, \u003Cstrong\u003Esmall bowel biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E is the gold standard for confirming the diagnosis of tropical sprue. This will typically shows villous atrophy, crypt hyperplasia, and increased inflammatory cells in the lamina propria. These findings, while not pathognomonic, are highly suggestive of tropical sprue when combined with the clinical picture and travel history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EColonoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E is not the preferred investigation for tropical sprue as the disease primarily affects the small intestine. While it may show some non-specific changes, it is not diagnostic for this condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStool culture\u003C/strong\u003E can be useful to rule out infectious causes of diarrhoea, but it will not confirm tropical sprue. The exact pathogen responsible for tropical sprue is unknown, and bacterial overgrowth is thought to be a consequence rather than the primary cause.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eabdominal CT scan\u003C/strong\u003E may show some non-specific findings such as bowel wall thickening or mesenteric lymphadenopathy, but it is not diagnostic for tropical sprue. It may be more useful in ruling out other causes of chronic diarrhoea.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ehydrogen breath test\u003C/strong\u003E can be used to diagnose small intestinal bacterial overgrowth, which may be present in tropical sprue. However, it is not specific for tropical sprue and does not provide the same diagnostic certainty as a small bowel biopsy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther useful investigations in the workup of tropical sprue include a D-xylose absorption test, which can help differentiate tropical sprue from other malabsorption syndromes, and serum albumin levels, which are often low due to protein-losing enteropathy. However, the small bowel biopsy remains the most definitive diagnostic test for tropical sprue.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Small bowel biopsy is the gold standard for diagnosing tropical sprue, showing villous atrophy and crypt hyperplasia.","Folate and vitamin B12 deficiencies are common in tropical sprue due to malabsorption.","D-xylose absorption test can help differentiate tropical sprue from other malabsorption syndromes."],"references":["Louis-Auguste J, Kelly P. Tropical Enteropathies. Curr Gastroenterol Rep 2017; 19: 29-37"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43887"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14117"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43887","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/43887"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-31T20:45:14+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T20:46:29+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6797"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58471"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"2436","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2436"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Fatigue","synonyms":["Tiredness","Lethargy","Daytime sleepiness"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-07-03T10:14:40+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-20T16:34:05+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"3"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"2969","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2969"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Tropical sprue","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-09-03T18:22:23+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-